message:
This is an improvement for stack overflow issue: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/65836411/aws-transcript-file-to-text-returns-nonsense/65863188#65863188.

In general, AWS SDK client should verify and where possible read input parameters for correctness.  It's very confusing to the client when there's no errors and yet, the transcript is wrong.

In this PR, I use javax.sound.sampled.AudioFormat.Encoding to automatically detect PCM encoding and sample rate.

author: shepazon
message:
Dockerfile fixes (#4377)

* Dockerfile compatibility for newer Swift versions

Versions of the Swift docker image for version 5.7 and later have differences
that prevented the Dockerfile's instructions from working correctly, and did
not work with the `swiftbuild` script.  This is fixed in this commit thusly:

* Changed the Dockerfile to pull the most recent Swift instead of Swift 5.6.
  This is done because the Swift 5.6 docker image doesn't work for ARM Macs.
* Changed the name of `swiftbuild` to `swiftbuild.py` to clarify that it's a
  Python script.
* Changed the Dockerfile to invoke `swiftbuild` by directly executing
  `python3.10 swiftbuild.py`. This both uses the name for the Python installed
  on the more recent image and is updated for the new name of the script.

* Reword dockerfile comment

* Tweak wording one more time.

---------

Co-authored-by: Eric Shepherd <sheppy@ip-172-31-45-50.us-east-2.compute.internal>
Co-authored-by: Steven Meyer <108885656+meyertst-aws@users.noreply.github.com>

author: shepazon
message:
Swift: Add mocking example (#5260)

This example demonstrates how to use a protocol to mock the AWS SDK for Swift, since Swift lacks the readwrite reflection required for traditional mocking. Passes the test (which is also the exemplar).

There is no build available on the web since this example is not one that corresponds to a particular function, but instead a technique for Swift developers using the SDK.

Once this PR is submitted, I'll start writing the AWS SDK for Swift Developer Guide chapter that will embed these snippets as it explains the mocking technique used here.

author: cpyle0819
message:
Add 'Shirriff' action to manage stale issues and PRs. (#3942)

Creates an Action named 'Shirriff' which runs the GitHub "stale"
action every day at 01:00 UTC. The action will mark issues older
than 14 days as 'status/stale' and add a comment. It will not
check issues with the 'type/epic' or 'status/icebox' labels.

This first iteration is debug-only. If the dry-run looks good we'll
turn off debug mode.

author: shepazon
message:
Add timer delay feature to SwiftUtilities module (#4197)

* Add new STimer struct to SwiftUtilities

The `STimer` struct is used to create and run timers. The first feature,
included in this PR, adds a function to wait until a given amount of time
expires, optionally printing messages before and/or after the delay.

This will replace the various delay functions that are currently individually
implemented in various examples and tests throughout the Swift SDK examples.

* Removed a commented-out block of code

author: shepazon
message:
Updates to build with Docker (#4236)

* Updates to build with Docker

Changes:

* Added a new `swiftbuild` tool in the `tools` directory. This Python
  tool is used by the Dockerfile to automate building the examples.
  The tool builds projects whose directories are given on the command
  line. Also supports running and testing the samples, suppressing
  warnings, and has a couple of options for altering the output of the
  command.
* Added the `.build` directory and the `Dockerfile` file to the new
  `.dockerignore` file, to reduce the size of the built image by not
  including build artifacts or the file used to build the image in
  the first place.
* Updated the `Dockerfile` to use Swift 5.6 since several examples
  require it, install Python for the build script to run, and the
  OpenSSL library and developer files needed to build using the AWS
  SDK for Swift. Finally, the `Dockerfile` now uses `swiftbuild` to
  build the examples instead of running Swift directly.

* Remove Dockerfile from .dockerignore

Also, fixes a couple of comments and adds a note to `README.md` pointing out
that some examples require newer versions of Swift than the minimum supported
by the SDK.

author: stewartsmith
message:
Move cpp lambda Dockerfile to Amazon Linux 2023 (#5028)

The current version of Amazon Linux is AL2023, thus it should be used as
the examples rather than AL2, which will be End of Life mid-2025.

For AL2023, we can skip weak dependencies, and by cleaning the dnf cache
we reduce the container image size (as we do not need to store the
downloaded yum repository metadata in the image).

In this case, the installed set of packages is smaller, and the
resulting zip file for the function is around 40% smaller!

AL2 based: 38MB extracted, 10.5MB compressed
AL2023 based: 22MB extracted, 6.6MB compressed

Memory consumption appears to be the same.

author: indrora
message:
Update the sample to be more chatty, handle several issues

The sample now outputs more information instead of just doing things
 silently; this just makes it a little easier to see what is going on.

 Additionally, there were some pretty nasty logic errors I discovered.
 Most aggregious of them was a failure to properly open files to write;
 this is because I used the wrong Open call (go wants `os.Create(...)`
 instead of `os.Open(...)`, which threw me off from working in Python).
 I've cleaned up those logic errors and added clearer error handling.
 Additionally, the logic for emptying a bucket is much cleaner.

author: indrora
message:
Get Go tests working

This commit makes sure that the Go tests pass -- at least, those that are run.

Added in this commit are a handful of gems:

* .nocitest disables running tests in a branch

author: Laren-AWS
message:
Python code example to demonstrate how to use the boto3 managed file transfer feature to manage uploads to and
downloads from an Amazon S3 bucket.

This example includes several subscripts that configure the transfer manager to upload and download files using
various settings, including standard transfer, multipart transfer, single-threaded transfer, and server-side
encryption.

The example is divided into two files, one for the main example code and one for user interaction.

file_transfer.py
  The main example code that contains the scripts to upload and download files.

demo_file_transfer.py
  The demo manager code that collects info from the user, reports results, and cleans up artifacts.

This commit also contains edits to code comments made by beckandros.

author: shepazon
message:
Improvements to swiftbuild.py tool (#5136)

Handle errors better when parsing the command line in the `swiftbuild` tool.
In addition, added code that checks each project directory for a file named
`test.sh`. If it exists, it is run instead of `swiftc test`, and its output
code signals sucess (0) or failure (any other value). This allows custom test
procedures.

Added a `test.sh` script to the `ListBuckets-Simple` example. This always
returns 0, signaling success, since there's no test for this example. Without
this, `swiftc test` fails, resulting in the test pass signaling a failure when
there isn't one.

As a bonus tweak, fixed a stray out-of-date syntax issue in the S3 basics
example's `Package.swift` file.

author: yuriolive
message:
Unit 'Seconds' is not supported by 'CPUUtilization' metric

Unit 'Seconds' is not supported by 'CPUUtilization' metric. 'CPUUtilization should use 'Percent' as Unit, or just be blank. CloudWatch alarm will get stuck in the INSUFFICIENT DATA state using 'Seconds' as Unit value. https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sdk-for-javascript/v2/developer-guide/cloudwatch-examples-creating-alarms.html should be changed too.

Correct typos

Words with 1 letter added, 1 letter removed, or 2 letters transposed.

or function, I fixed it in both places.)

words in the source code.

Creates an Action named 'Shirriff' which runs the GitHub "stale"
action every day at 01:00 UTC. The action will mark issues older
than 14 days as 'status/stale' and add a comment. It will not
check issues with the 'type/epic' or 'status/icebox' labels.

message:
Rust: Updated send-email.rs for Contact list with more that one contact, SES (#5202)

* Update send-email.rs

cs is being returned without a comma. eg:
user@example.comuser2@example.com...
Causes Exception:
Error: BadRequestException(BadRequestException { message: Some("Illegal address"), meta: ErrorMetadata { code: Some("BadRequestException"), message: Some("Illegal address"), extras: Some({"aws_request_id": "da0bf20a-52b3-4acc-bb22-eec27cf68322"}) } })

If the contact list has more that one contact it will fail.

* Update send-email.rs - Fixed for Contact List with more that one

Fixed.
cs is being generated as String, if the Contact list has more that one contact it will fail. eg:
user@example.comuser2@example.com...
Causes Exception:
Error: BadRequestException(BadRequestException { message: Some("Illegal address"), meta: ErrorMetadata { code: Some("BadRequestException"), message: Some("Illegal address"), extras: Some({"aws_request_id": "da0bf20a-52b3-4acc-bb22-eec27cf68322"}) } })

cs is now a Vec<String> and is directly assigned to dest.to_addresses

* Update send-email.rs

rustfmt
